    "author_association": "NONE",
    "body": "Hmm, I'm confused, obviously users can scale by whatever constant they would like, but seems like a different issue.  The name percentage implies 0-100, which is not what the function returns.\n\nFrom https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Percentage - \"In mathematics, a percentage is a number or ratio expressed as a fraction of 100.\" \n\nAll examples I can find in numpy/scipy behave with 0-100 scaling:\n\nhttp://docs.scipy.org/doc/numpy-dev/reference/generated/numpy.percentile.html\nhttp://docs.scipy.org/doc/scipy-0.13.0/reference/generated/scipy.stats.percentileofscore.html\nhttps://docs.scipy.org/doc/scipy-0.14.1/reference/generated/scipy.misc.imresize.html\nhttp://docs.scipy.org/doc/scipy/reference/generated/scipy.stats.scoreatpercentile.html\nhttp://docs.scipy.org/doc/scipy/reference/generated/scipy.ndimage.filters.percentile_filter.html\n\nWhile obviously like you say, the user can scale the output by whatever number they'd like, bugs crop up if the scale isn't what they expect, no?  Why not make the function the same as what the user should expect, so that it is easiest to get the scaling to where it should be?\n"
  },
